IN the hands of Erasmus Latin is, before all things, a living language. His Colloqaiea not

only form a store-house of idiom‚ but they exhibit real dramatis power. In the present selection variety both in subject and style has been specially aimed at. Besides the bright and playful dialogue‚ the reader will find here many passages which, though dramatis in form, are excellent and at the same time easy examples of the narrative and reflective styles of Latin Prose. The original text of Erasmus has been freely dealt with, in order to secure greater simplicity of vocabulary and syntax; and some of the dialogues have been considerably shortened. It is hoped that a selection of ‘dramatis idylls‚' thus adapted, will prove a useful and entertaining reading-book for young students.

G. M. E. August, 1906.
